#6F6F6F>(8/16/02 8:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> Could yales and project orion please tell me your reasoning behind your opinions on nuclear power in space. Other members are welcome to state why their opinions are what they are. But please, no name calling. Just state your reasoning and leave it to that. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 764<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/16/02 10:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> I'll chime in:  Chemical rockets have been around for a looooong time, and the best they have been able to do is send 3 men to the moon and back.  A typical Saturn V/Apollo moon rocket had a mass ration of 600 to 1.  In other words, if the entire vehicle at liftoff weighed 600 kilos, then only 1 kilo returned at the end of the mission... quite a waste in material.  On the nuclear side, an Orion type vehicle would have a mass ratio of 1.5 to 1 with the original model (Project Orion, p. 190-191)<br>
<br>
So efficiency is a big reason.  But the biggest reason for me is the higher velocities that could be attained, making manned voyages to the other planets in our solar system much more practical.<br>
<br>
A six to nine month voyage to Mars could be reduced to a few weeks time under a nuclear propelled spacecraft... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=discovery1>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/16/02 11:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Thanks for your input</span><hr size=1> Thanks zaphod4468. I appreciate your input. Again I encourage anyone to state their reasoning behind their opinions on nuclear power in space, but especially yales and projectorion.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/16/02 11:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> I disagree slightly with Zaphod in that I don't think we should be launching Orions from the ground (I'm not dead set against it, I just need to know more facts) but I think if we plan to get anywhere in the Solar System cheaply, quick, and in comfort the use of Orion type spacecraft is our only real option.  I liked the already mentioned plan of using Sea Dragons to lift payloads into space than use the Orions for interplanetary travel from there.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 8/16/02 11:57:52 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uatomicredux.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AtomicRedux</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.geocities.com/marsmetaphysics/Cap0202.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 72<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/17/02 12:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/images/ezboard/user_images/Cap0202.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> How about the fact that the best chemical rockets can only achieve a Specific Impulse (Isp) of about 430 seconds? A Nuclear Thermal Rocket (NTR) using lightweight hydrogen as fuel on the other hand, can attain an Isp of 900 seconds. And that’s only what has already been tested under the NERVA program. An Orion-type propulsion system would have a much higher Isp then the engines tested during the NERVA program.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 766<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/17/02 2:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> I'm more of an advocate for the space use only of an orion too... but a ground launch would be spectacular!<br>
<br>
The first gen Orion's may have had an ISP in the 2000-3000 range, second gen ISP in the 4000-6000 range.  Other systems have higher ISP but little thrust (Ion drive on DS1 for example) but an Orion has high ISP <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> AND</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> high thrust.<br>
<br>
Two advanced &quot;hypothetical&quot; Orion vehicles were worked on: the more powerful design had an ISP of 20,000 and a thrust of 40 million pounds, with a mission velocity of 500,000 ft/sec (nearly 60 kilometers per second!)  At that speed, one could travel the distance from the Earth to the moon in under an hour, but it took the Apollo astronauts days... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uatomicredux.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AtomicRedux</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.geocities.com/marsmetaphysics/Cap0202.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/17/02 2:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/images/ezboard/user_images/Cap0202.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> Don't foget half of fuel requirments for space travel are slowing down. If you were going 60 km/sec to the Moon it would be very hard to slow down. The mean speed of the Apollo missions was 1.5 km/sec  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 771<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/17/02 3:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1>