of such a magnitude as to wipe out over 95% of all life on the surface of the planet. One look at the cratered moon tells you we are a sitting duck to space debris like asteroids and comets. What we think of as the Earth is but a thin segmented skin floating on a liquid mantle. Volcano's and Asteroids have almost sterilised this planet on more than a few occasions but if that isn't enough there is the threat from biochemical and nuclear weapons aswell. <br>
<br>
I would like to see humanity expand beyond the Earth. I'd like to see new heroes and adventurers explore untouched frontiers. I feel stifled here. I want affordable space travel thats available to everyone. Not just the military elite. Nuclear power is the only way of doing this right now. I would definately advocate looking into Orion technology to achieve it. The idea of ground launching is generally ignored because of the fallout which might be produced by an extensive program. What I would like to see is more research directed at ways to reduce the environmental impact. Clean bombs might not be possible but &quot;cleaner&quot; ones might. What we need to realise is that an extensive program really isn't necessary. A couple of big Orions is all we would ever have to launch. They would be capable of carrying the industrial infrastructure necessary to utilise space resources and build new Orions in space. A couple of carefully designed Orions shouldn't have a very great impact on the environment. Remember that hundreds of extremely high yield megaton devices were tested back in the 50's and 60's. All but one of the blasts from an Orion would be relatively clean airbursts and an initial groundburst might be avoided aswell. I believe that the payoff would outweigh any minimal effect on the environment but ofcourse we wont know unless some research is done. We have to ask the question of whether or not it is feasible and not simply laugh. <br>
<br>
A couple of Orions in space would mean a destination point for orbital vehicles where they can refuel. Interplanetary vehicles like Orion are capable of taking hundreds of passengers to the far reaches of the system. Also the industry would then be in place to start major engineering constructions off Earth. I realise Orion is a tall ask though. The public isn't ready yet.<br>
 <br>
I strongly support all nuclear space technology as I believe it to be a miraculous source of energy that we are fortunate to posess and should utilise as best we can. Not doing so would not only be foolish but suicidal. Whoever controls this genie has the power to both create and destroy. Whoever wields it alone is unstoppable. The only defense against nuclear fire is nuclear fire and if you don't have it then you are hiding behind somebody else who does. We may not like it but that is the way of the world and the only option is to put up with it until we find a way off it. Nuclear power is here to stay. We might aswell use it as a means of expanding beyond the Earth.<br>
 <br>
After we have colonised the system we will look back and wonder how we ever survived on a single planet for so long. Even the nuclear genie will lose much of its very frightening aspect among the infinite reaches of space. Because inertia weapons could do far more damage. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 8/18/02 6:17:24 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 781<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/18/02 12:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why?</span><hr size=1> If a so-called &quot;clean nuke&quot; was ever created then Orion could be built and sold to the public... on the flip side, a clean bomb would be much more likely to be used in a war. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1877<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/18/02 7:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Research.</span><hr size=1> It's unlikely to happen in my opinion but &quot;cleaner&quot; nukes are feasible. Especially when you consider the application. Virtually all past research has been directed towards weapons development. Fallout was never a major concern. Collateral damage was the aim. Today scientists are turning towards smaller more tactical nukes. That approach is more in line with Orion's needs. Not identical though. Pulse units must exert maximum kinetic energy to a reaction mass which impinges against the pusher plate. The energy created is enormous and we can afford to reduce it in exchange for a reduction in fallout if that is found to be possible. Still plenty of energy left to reach space. I'm certain that research directed narrowly at making &quot;cleaner&quot; bombs could be successful.<br>
First of all we know that the blasts will be airbursts. We have to ask how we can best reduce the contamination of bomb fragments, atmospheric dust and water vapour. Look at different geographical sites and compare quantities of matter which could become residual fallout. Would certain times of year be better? Can the bombs casing be composed of a material that disintegrates completely or should we go the other way and ensure it breaks up into a limited number of schrapnel pieces that are recoverable. Can we use a new kind of trigger other than Plutonium or enriched Uranium? Weapons are designed to last decades but pulse units might be constructed and used immediately. Can a shortlived heavy element work? We have to ask questions and try out fresh ideas. See what works. Get the zero radiation myth out of our heads. There is no need for radiation levels to be eradicated. Only reduced to acceptable levels. What's an acceptable level? Radiation is all around us already and even a threefold increase in background levels likely wouldn't hurt us. More likely make us healthier through hormetic effect. What would a new improved Orion designed for minimal fallout still produce? I don't know. Let's find out. Even the 50's version is estimated to have created less than 1% of the fallout level at that time being produced by weapons testing. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 8/18/02 7:58:49 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 55<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/20/02 8:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  spacecrafts using  nuclear propulsion</span><hr size=1> Nuclear propulsion is essential to space flight for two<br>
