<br>
The substantial arguments about it stem from doubts about the safety -not of Orion itself or the bombs going into it- but the safety of having refined radioactive materials and strong neutron sources in circulation. The risks of it being diverted are too much. To clandestine weapons production -either governmental or any groups who want it- or openly granting a free hand to governments to make &amp; use nuclear weapons.<br>
Also involved is the problem of nuclear waste. Although completing the fuel cycle could possibly remove some of that, there's always the simple waste from working with the stuff: contaminated tools, buildings, and even cleaning supplies. This is aggravated by the crappy records of governmental nuclear programs: they considered themselves to be on a war footing, so any price was not too high to pay to build the things. Damn the environment, the workers or even the citizens.<br>
Argurably, this is the major emotionally charged argument against nuclear. It's got a terrible history, because governments and mega-corporates raped the Earth, and callously killed and maimed people to make horrific killing weapons.<br>
<br>
 The reasoning seems to be that if we remove all materials and technologies required to make bombs, the problems of nuclear weapons will go away.<br>
From that stance, Orion is a terrible risk, because it makes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> weapons usable</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> nuclear materials a strong economic attraction, and that makes weapons more likely. Similarly, Breeder reactors and MOX fueled reactors are also risky, because of the &quot;Plutonium Economy&quot; they'd make (Anti-nuclear coined phrase. Having a use for Pu, and a reason other than weapons for it to be made and dealt with).<br>
<br>
I don't buy it. First of all, it's like blaming your spare tire for the flat tire you've suffered (Nuclear bombs don't kill people, people kill people).  If you don't think you can control the governments and megalomaniac politicians &amp; generals, ban the objects and techniques they're using.<br>
 I try to think like Theodore Taylor seems to have said: If we look at nuclear power, the immediately evident possibilities are terrible. But if we dig around a little deeper, we can find hope in it. Use the really interestiing technologies made possible <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> only</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by nuclear energy -even up to and including the release of it in explosive devices!<br>
 He said we could disentangle nuclear power from the horror of Hiroshima &amp; Nagasaki.<br>
Besides, if we can't control the megalomaniacs to the extent of forbidding the simple use of nuclear weapons, then what possiblity is there to force on them a universal ban of the necessary technologies and the materials involved?<br>
<br>
It should be acceptable to state that we could safely use nuclear materials. That it won't mean we're giving the militarists and terrorists a free hand in making weapons -there's no sane reason to doubt this. (first no-nukes objection)<br>
<br>
It's arguably a given, that we could safely get the nuclear materials up to the ships in space. Once there, there's really no reasonable argument to using it -even in an Orion engine. What's there to pollute in the solar wind? (next 'anti' argument)<br>
Maybe we could get clean bombs, and the political will to do a ground launch Orion, but space use is an option.<br>
<br>
Nuclear thermal is proven in tests. Even its relatively marginal performance greatly improves our ability to get around space.<br>
<br>
Nuclear Pulse is theoretically well thought out, and proven in tests with sub-scale models. There's no reasonable doubt that it could be made to work.<br>
Nuke pulse <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>greatly</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> improves our ability to get around. Take all the doubts about our ability to safely get people around in space, and throw them out.<br>
 With Orion, we've got it made.<br>
 A few months travel time to Jupiter and its moons, in huge massively strong ships revolutionizes our understanding of what space travel could be like. Maybe only a slight exaggeration to say it could be as routine and safe as &quot;trek&quot; makes it out to be. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 8/23/02 3:02:19 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 12:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> Good points John Franz.  To be honest, I had been a little worried by the possibility of the fuel pellets being usurped by terrorists, but with careful accounting and oversight there's little reason to fear especially once the fuel is in space where the danger is greatly reduced.  A new question just popped up in my head.  On a ship that carries private citizens the way airlines do, should the compartments that hold the nuclear fuel be accessible only through spacewalks as something of an extra security layer?  Or maybe have a well shielded little eva carrier?  What kind of security measures should be in place on the Orion ship itself especially if its function is to carry members of the public? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 8/24/02 12:03:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 841<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 4:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> Good point... yes, the pulse units would need to be fairly secure, behind a locked hatch with limited access.  Necessary personel only.  A typical pulse unit on a 4000 ton class Orion could weigh as much as 1870 lbs. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Spaceship, p.160)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1911<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 10:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A question to yales and projectorion</span><hr size=1> Spaceship hijacking is a phenomenon which should be planned for in advance. We should learn from our experience with airplane terrorists. I am one of those who see's the military as an essential part of space exploration. Any spaceship, nuclear or not should be stopped if it is seen to be approaching an inhabited World(Planet or other habitat) at dangerous velocity or without permission. Inertia weapons will be the real threat. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> 